{"slideshow_credits": null, "snippet": "There are many ways, besides the well-known sampling error, to get things wrong in polling....", "abstract": "The Upshot; recent paper examining over 4,000 late-campaign public polls for state-level presidential, Senate and governor races between 1998 and 2014 finds historic margin of error is much higher than touted 3 percentage point standard; reasons cited include misconceptions about sampling subset; revelations mean even if one candidate ends up with as much as five-point lead in early November, they may not end up victor. ", "section_name": "The Upshot", "print_page": "18", "document_type": "article", "byline": {"person": [{"firstname": "David", "role": "reported", "lastname": "ROTHSCHILD", "rank": 1, "organization": ""}, {"firstname": "Sharad", "role": "reported", "lastname": "GOEL", "rank": 2, "organization": ""}], "original": "By DAVID ROTHSCHILD and SHARAD GOEL"}, "web_url": "http://www.nytimes.com/2016/10/06/upshot/when-you-hear-the-margin-of-error-is-plus-or-minus-3-percent-think-7-instead.html", "lead_paragraph": "There are many ways, besides the well-known sampling error, to get things wrong in polling.", "headline": {"print_headline": "If a Poll\u2019s Margin of Error Is Plus or Minus 3 Points, Think 7", "main": "When You Hear the Margin of Error Is Plus or Minus 3 Percent, Think 7 Instead", "content_kicker": "Survey Says?", "kicker": "The Upshot"}, "_id": "57f4dd3c95d0e021d798a2e3", "word_count": "1006", "multimedia": [{"height": 126, "url": "images/2016/09/29/upshot/margin-chart-1475107465117/margin-chart-1475107465117-thumbWide.png", "legacy": {"wideheight": "126", "wide": "images/2016/09/29/upshot/margin-chart-1475107465117/margin-chart-1475107465117-thumbWide.png", "widewidth": "190"}, "subtype": "wide", "width": 190, "type": "image"}, {"height": 766, "url": "images/2016/09/29/upshot/margin-chart-1475107465117/margin-chart-1475107465117-articleLarge.png", "legacy": {"xlarge": "images/2016/09/29/upshot/margi